node.text:
Throwback! - it’s crazy to think how long we’ve doing this. I made this on the old diy time-lapse dolly I built in college.
The first location was from the “There’s an Alien On Your Head” video shoot. Niko shot Clint with an Arrow. 
The last part outside is from “Bark Ops”. Both very fun film shoots! 
And of course, Studio 3. The first Corridor digital office. Maybe we’ll be seeing more of it?

Music! The track Rain from amazing artist Rob Scallon! @robscallon. He has a super fun YouTube channel if you like music. 
Also, Freddie being Freddie haha.

node.text:
Truly a highlight of my career so far. To have someone as accomplished as Seth Rogen not only validate our work but be enthusiastic to join us was very special. He was just so nice and laid back and genuinely cares about the filmmaking craft. It was a joy to work with him! Hopefully we’ll do more together in the future!
The first of 2 episode with him went live yesterday! I recommend checking it out! He has some amazing stories!

node.text:
SO excited to finally share this!!! I helped make an official Onewheel commercial!! 
I’m very proud of how this spot turned out, and wanna give HUGE props to Future Motion for approving a commercial that barely even shows their own product!! The mad lads!

I accepted this project because I believed in the idea. It was just crazy enough to be brilliant, and bonkers enough to actually work.

Big thanks to Cade (@cadevlacos), the project-lead on this. He shot all the footage and edited the video together. Without him this video probably wouldn’t have survived when management started getting nervous. Definitely go give him a follow!

There is a TON of VFX work here!! It’s a lot more complex than it may appear. I created new clean plates from scratch for every shot. That involved 3D tracking each shot, rebuilding the scene geometry in 3D, and then projection-painting “clean” areas of the image onto that. Then I just repeated that over and over until the Onewheel (and legs/shadow) are gone from the entire shot!

But that’s just the start. You then gotta rotoscope back in the riders! And more than that, you actually have to rebuild the legs any time they’re blocked from view by the Onewheel. The fender/tire blocks the view of the back foot in almost every shot. That was a big challenge. 

And finally, the shadow was recreated on every shot too. I couldn’t just “remove” the Onewheel from the shadow, so remaking it from scratch was the only way. Fortunately Red Giant makes a great shadow plugin that I used on all the rotoscope layers of the riders to make new shadows.

I’ll see about maybe making and posting a breakdown video soon because the concept is SUPER interesting and I figured out some cool new workflows for it!

Oh and that sweet Pint render at the end was animated by me using Fields in C4D and modeled by @latenightrenders!

node.text:
My newest render! Clint challenged the community to create a render that participated in a huge digital Rube Goldberg machine and this was our entry!! 

This was a huge collab with Jordan (@vfxwithjordan) and he killed it simulating the zombie horde in Houdini!! It was like a 250Gb sim haha 😅. I’m still hoping to get better at Houdini. Though honestly I’m still happy situation what I can do in C4D. 

The zombies are actually scans of some of the corridor crew members! The upstairs was a highly polished and optimized photoscan of the smash room where we legit play tons of smash bros. Obviously I had to include the game where I beat Clint 😈😈😈

Using a bunch of megascans textures and assets I built out the dungeon area. I like the method of what I got with the fire torches! Basically use a fire element as an emissive texture, but mostly just use an non-visible octane light in the spot of the torch for the actual light. 
There are several things I wish I could still fix but sometimes you just gotta move on!

node.text:
I made a new thing! We did a Bob Ross challenge and tried to follow along with the show while building out a sunrise landscape in 3D. It was stressful lol… it was hilarious to see everyone think Peter made this instead of me during the voting session. 

I opted for a hyper stylized direction instead of trying to compete in a photo realism competition with a bunch of trees. I experimented a tiny bit with different SSS shaders but really didn’t have much time to do this. It was super fun! Just not as relaxing as Bob Ross’s show always is haha. Also I really wish I could go back and add something to fill the empty lawn area. Maybe a campfire. Oh well, it’s better to move on and finish than to work on something forever.

Are you satisfied by this perfect fit? 

My latest attempt at trying to make a really pleasing piece of art, which you can find on Corridor Crew! And of course, I love loops so it HAD to loop!

A lot went into making this shot. Obviously the sound design was a very important aspect, and is where I began. I found a few sounds I liked and formed and idea around them. I’ve been getting really into layered sound design lately haha. It’s fun!

As for technical visual stuff, that was the real challenge! In theory the idea is simple enough: Cutout a puzzle shape from a pre-UV’d plane, then extrude that into a block that gets animated into place. Getting everything to actually work was not simple lol. 

The animation was a combo of real rigid body physics of it getting tossed across the ground roughly into the right position, then animating the strength of a C4D constraint modifier to get it perfectly into position. The drop and bounce were hand animated. 

The last frame of this post is actually my first proof of concept that never made it into the Crew video! What I really love about that shot (that I unfortunately couldn’t replicate later) was the wobbly bounciness the puzzle piece has sliding across the ground. It’s such a realistic looking slide! In the final thing it’s mostly framed out anyway.

A surprising challenge that I’m really proud to have pulled off was getting the ground texture to tile properly. I had to dial in the scale of the texture so that it stretched perfectly across the length of 4 pieces, like within 0.0001cm accuracy haha. I also fully did the animation of the red piece twice so that I could smoothly transition between the end and beginning of the shot in after effects for a smooth loop. You can see that transition in the Wireframe shot!

Anyway! Let me know if you like these detailed descriptions of what goes into these posts! Any info you’d like to hear more or less about?

8 years ago I proposed to @jsmiley3 🥰😍

I surprised her too! With the help of some friends I planted a metal rose with the ring inside at the Santa Monica beach. The two of us were on a walk and “happened” to wander on by this interesting little thing in the sand. Of course I was “curious” so i knelt down to check it out and held it up for Jenna to look at as well. “What in the world?? How random! I didn’t know metal grew like this!” I don’t think I’d ever been so nervous in my life. 

At this point she still didn’t expect anything. That is until she saw the look in my eyes as I opened the rose to reveal the ring, at which point she totally understood what was happening and went into utter shock haha. Then she said no and we broke up and haven’t talked to each other since...

But for real though she’s been a total angel through this whole injury debacle I’ve been going through. She’s so incredibly patient and caring and I couldn’t possibly be any luckier to have ended up with her 🤗🤗🤗🤗

Sound on! I LOVED diving into the trees like this and I wanted to share the sounds of this forest as well. The Pacific Northwest is such a beautiful place. 

My first attempt I totally flew into the trees and crashed, but the drone (DJI FPV) was just fine and I got this shot right after!

This drone is interesting. It’s hefty and sluggish, and the footage isn’t as stable as Reelsteady GoPro stuff. However, I kinda like the less “fake stabilized” feel Reelsteady can often overdo. Plus the safety and convenience features are really nice to have. I haven’t flown my normal freestyle quad since December actually. 
If you saw the attack on Titan video, the fight scene was filmed with this drone and the Mavic air 2! Now I’m just waiting till this new controller works with all the other FPV drones I have haha. 

Also, I hope you dig the sound in this! I’ve been on a bit of a sound design kick lately. We just finished a new round of Satisfying Renders and I was pretty pleased with my sound design there too.

Also also, the drone is fine after the end of this video. The drone barely even noticed hitting the branch and kept going haha

node.text:
I’m overjoyed by the incredible response to the Scale of Attack on Titan video!! In just 9 days it broke 4mil on YouTube which makes it the most popular Special I’ve made yet! Well, in terms of view count velocity anyway haha. Seriously, thank you to everyone who watched and shared it. This was absolutely a labor of love.

I wanted to share the final shot of the video cuz I’m pretty proud of it haha. I can talk for ages about what went into this shot. Sam modeled a Titan version of me in character creator and spiced up Peter’s body mocap with facial capture animation. Daniel held the camera here and Matt chose the music! I built out the scene and rendered/composited it all. It all really came together!! 
I did some fun new things for the render side of it, using CamTrackAR for the fake but “real handheld” motion after the transformation. I also feel like I finally figured out camera mapping in Octane render and was able to get proper parallax motion of the background as the camera got “closer” to the overpass after the Titan grabbed the camera. Anyway. It was super fun to make a Titan transformation shot IRL! 

Seriously though I’m still just so dang proud of this video and the team behind it. Lots of help from Peter and Matt with VFX and editing, but also Sam’s expertise with mocap came in clutch! and of course Jake with the Meme’s! 
If you haven’t seen the epic 18 minute “Making Of” documentary about this video on the Corridor website, I highly recommend checking it out. You can get a free trial!

Also... I wanted to say that I’m proud of myself too. It’s been really hard lately. You guys know about the collarbone but I also broke my shoulder a few weeks before that. I was literally in the middle of scheduling surgery when the collarbone break happened. That surgery still needs to happen. I’ve also had a lot going on in my personal life but I’m in therapy now and it’s helping. But in spite of all that, we still managed to not only finish the video, but make it better than it was going to be. It was a painful time but it was also just so fun and rewarding to create this. To have it become a success on YouTube is just simply a bonus.
